Phidippides’s α running ‘the 130 miles from Athens to Sparta in two days was a mighty seat, until the Spartan runner Anystis and Alexander the Great’s courier Philonides ran the 148 miles from Sicyon to Elis in a day. At the present day indeed we are aware that some men can last out 128 miles in the circus, and that reeently in the consulship of Fon- teius and Vipstanus a boy of 8 ran 68 miles between noon and evening. The marvellous nature of this seat will only get across to us in full measure if we reflect that Tiberius Nero eompleted by carriage the longest twenty-four hours' journey on record when hastening to Germany to his brother Drusus who was ill: this measured 182 miles.
